A figure is constructed from unit cubes. Each cube shares at least one face with another cube. What is the minimum number of cubes needed to build a figure with the front and side views shown?

\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[scale=0.5]{images/views1.png}
\end{center}

}

\textbf{Answer:} There are only two ways to construct a solid from three cubes so that each cube shares a face with at least one other:

\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[scale=0.5]{images/views_soln1.png}
\end{center}

Neither of these configurations has both the front and side views shown. The four-cube configuration has the required front and side views. Thus at least $\boxed{4}$ cubes are necessary.
\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[scale=0.5]{images/views_soln2.png}
\end{center}
